  "target_response": {
    "text": "Before moving your sessions, try extending sleep — 6.8 hours is on the short side for someone training regularly, and dragging through morning workouts is the predictable result of a modest, chronic shortfall rather than anything wrong with mornings themselves. Since your sleep is manually logged and I don't have recovery or heart-rate data, I can't cross-check other signals, so treat this as the honest first hypothesis. Push bedtime earlier in small steps until the morning heaviness lifts; most people feel the difference quickly. If a genuinely earlier bedtime isn't realistic with your life, then shifting training later is a perfectly good plan B — consistency matters more than time of day. Worth one distinction: dragging that improves with more sleep is benign, but crushing sleepiness that persists no matter how long you're in bed, or loud snoring with gasping awakenings, deserves a medical conversation.",
